f the cited landscapes. Literature was found for a total of 70 cultural landscapes, including 8 cultural landscapes that form part of the AMNC. Publications issued before 2000 were not considered, nor gray literature (with few exceptions), and the scope was limited by the exclusive use of publications in English. The Mediterranean region has many models to offer for sustainable land-use management. It is not only a biodiversity hotspot, but also has a rich history of cultural landscapes. Many of these landscapes are characterized by a specific dominant feature like tree-crops (mainly olives, chestnuts, cork oaks and almonds). The traditional land management practices have created a socio-ecological system beneficial for people and the environment and important to protect at a European and global scale. Executive summary V ANALYSIS OF KNOWLEDGE ON CULTURAL LANDSCAPES AT THE MEDITERRANEAN LEVEL IUCN-Med would like to thank the partners of the Alliance for Mediterranean Nature & Culture for their valuable expertise and insights. This report would not have been possible without their continuing work and focus on the cultural landscapes situated in the Mediterranean region. Contributors and members of the AMNC: GOB Menorca - https://www.gobmenorca.com/ Mediterranean Institute for Nature and Anthropos (MedINA) - https://med-ina.org/ Global Diversity Foundation - https://global-diversity.org/ Moroccan Biodiversity and Livelihoods Association (MBLA) - https://www.mblaassociation.org/ Society for the Protection of Nature in Lebanon (SPNL) - https://www.spnl.org/ Shouf Biosphere Reserve - http://shoufcedar.org/ Trashumancia y Naturaleza (TyN) - https://trashumanciaynaturaleza.org/ WWF Spain - https://www.wwf.es/ WWF Portugal ANP - https://www.natureza-portugal.org/ Yolda - https://yolda.org.tr/ WWF Tunisia - https://www.wwf.tn/ EuroNatur - https://www.euronatur.org/en Tour du Valat - https://tourduvalat.org/en/ Acknowledgements VI ANALYSIS OF KNOWLEDGE ON CULTURAL LANDSCAPES 